{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:36:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14258"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14258"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.41,0.23,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57175"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6953"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42634"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2403"},{"type":"tags","id":"3465"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9101"},{"type":"tags","id":"9124"},{"type":"tags","id":"9127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17176"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57175"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of constant pain in his left lower abdomen. The pain is described as dull and aching, with occasional sharp exacerbations. He reports no nausea, vomiting, or changes in bowel habits. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly unwell. His pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 116/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.7\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with some tenderness in the left iliac fossa, but no guarding or rebound tenderness. Bowel sounds are present. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous contrast is performed (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antibiotics and review","Image-guided percutaneous drainage","Laparoscopy and drainage","Laparotomy and drainage","Hartmann\u0027s procedure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with acute diverticulitis complicated by a pericolic abscess. The clinical picture of fever and left iliac fossa tenderness, along with CT findings of a thickened sigmoid colon and a pericolic abscess, confirms this diagnosis. The management approach depends on the extent of the disease process and the patient\u0027s general condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImage-guided percutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management in this case. For stable patients with diverticular abscesses larger than 3-4 cm, percutaneous drainage guided by CT or ultrasound is the preferred approach. This minimally invasive procedure can effectively drain the abscess while avoiding the risks associated with surgery. It is typically combined with intravenous antibiotics. The exact measurement is not listed in the above scan but it can be seen to be a sizeable collection\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics and review\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be appropriate for uncomplicated diverticulitis or small abscesses less than 3-4 cm in size. However, given the larger size of this abscess, antibiotics alone are unlikely to be sufficient, and drainage is warranted to expedite recovery and prevent complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is more invasive than percutaneous drainage and is generally reserved for cases where percutaneous drainage is not feasible or has failed. While it can be effective, it carries higher risks of complications and a longer recovery time compared to percutaneous drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is even more invasive and is typically reserved for cases with diffuse peritonitis, perforation, or failed minimally invasive approaches. In this relatively stable patient with a localized abscess, open surgery would be overly aggressive as an initial approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHartmann\u0027s procedure\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves resection of the diseased segment of colon with end colostomy formation, is a major surgery typically performed in emergency situations such as perforated diverticulitis with generalised peritonitis or in cases of failed conservative management. It would be excessive for this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter successful drainage, the patient should be monitored closely. If symptoms resolve and inflammatory markers improve, he can be discharged on oral antibiotics with follow-up. Colonoscopy is typically recommended 6-8 weeks after the acute episode to rule out underlying malignancy. In some cases, elective sigmoid colectomy may be considered to prevent recurrence, especially in younger patients or those with recurrent episodes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Image-guided percutaneous drainage is the preferred initial management for stable patients with diverticular abscesses larger than 3-4 cm.","Antibiotics alone are typically sufficient for uncomplicated diverticulitis or small abscesses (\u003C3-4 cm).","Surgical intervention is reserved for patients with peritonitis, perforation, or failed conservative management."],"references":["Williams S, Bjarnason I, Hayee B, et al. Diverticular disease: update on pathophysiology, classification and\u00a0management. Frontline Gastroenterol 2023; 15:50-50. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38487561/","Sacks OA, Hall J. Management of Diverticulitis A Review. JAMA Surg 2024; 159:696-703. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamasurgery/article-abstract/2817649"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42634"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14258"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21053"},{"type":"media","id":"21054"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21110"},{"type":"media","id":"21111"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21053"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aJ7VpxJ5aqsixjR8JXi6wjxkWDXDcH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aJ7VpxJ5aqsixjR8JXi6wjxkWDXDcH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":899,"height":635}},{"type":"media","id":"21054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21054"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/j0hVVWZHSH6zszNwcVOlJWktxnYf94.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/j0hVVWZHSH6zszNwcVOlJWktxnYf94.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":706,"height":843}},{"type":"media","id":"21110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21110"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/OsVRczkHZoXcGIQr44b44tSpADtIq0.jpg","thumbUrl":"ht